05130nmm a2200649Ia 9781501708022DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016050595  a97815017080227 a10.7591/97815017080222doi  a(DE-B1597)492918  a(OCoLC)962025801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aE97.65.N4 4aE97.65.N404a378.1/982970742322300aI Am Where I Come From :bNative American College Students and Graduates Tell Their Life Stories /ced. by Andrew C. Garrod, Melanie Benson Taylor, Robert Kilkenny. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The organizing principle for this anthology is the common Native American heritage of its authors; and yet that thread proves to be the most tenuous of all, as the experience of indigeneity differs radically for each of them. While many experience a centripetal pull toward a cohesive Indian experience, the indications throughout these essays lean toward a richer, more illustrative panorama of difference. What tends to bind them together are not cultural practices or spiritual attitudes per se, but rather circumstances that have no exclusive province in Indian country: that is, first and foremost, poverty, and its attendant symptoms of violence, substance abuse, and both physical and mental illness. Education plays a critical role in such lives: many of the authors recall adoring school as young people, as it constituted a place of escape and a rare opportunity to thrive. While many of the writers do return to their tribal communities after graduation, ideas about 'home' become more malleable and complicated."—from the IntroductionI Am Where I Come From presents the autobiographies of thirteen Native American undergraduates and graduates of Dartmouth College, ten of them current and recent students. Twenty years ago, Cornell University Press published First Person, First Peoples: Native American College Graduates Tell Their Life Stories, also about the experiences of Native American students at Dartmouth College. I Am Where I Come From addresses similar themes and experiences, but it is very much a new book for a new generation of college students.Three of the essays from the earlier book are gathered into a section titled "Continuing Education," each followed by a shorter reflection from the author on his or her experience since writing the original essay. All three have changed jobs multiple times, returned to school for advanced degrees, started and increased their families, and, along the way, continuously revised and refined what it means to be Indian.The autobiographies contained in I Am Where I Come From explore issues of native identity, adjustment to the college environment, cultural and familial influences, and academic and career aspirations. The memoirs are notable for their eloquence and bravery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian college studentszNew HampshirezHanovervBiography. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducation (Higher)zNew HampshirezHanover. 0aMinority college graduateszNew HampshirezHanovervBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aNative American Studies.  aNative American, Indian, student, racism, difference, education, tribal communities, autobiography, Dartmouth College.1 aGarrod, Andrew C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKilkenny, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLomawaima, K. Tsianina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Melanie Benson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go